\begin{abstract}
BF16 LLM inference is non-deterministic: the same input at different batch
sizes produces different output tokens. Yuan et al.~\citep{yuan2025numerical}
(NeurIPS 2025) recently characterized the phenomenon on reasoning models and
proposed LayerCast, a BF16-weights-FP32-compute baseline, at the cost of
upcasting weights to FP32 on every matmul.

We target \emph{token-wise} determinism (identical output tokens across
batch sizes), and trace the dominant obstacle to cuBLAS's dynamic split-K
selection in GEMM. We close that source with two backends that avoid
LayerCast's bandwidth penalty. A precision amplification argument shows that
FP32 reduction drives the non-associativity error below BF16's quantization
step whenever $K<K_{\max}\!\approx\!7{,}700$; we implement this as a cuBLASLt
wrapper. A fixed-plan Triton kernel gives bit-exact batch-invariant GEMM
output by construction at every $K$ (i.e., the matmul result is bit-identical
across batch sizes, which is a strictly stronger guarantee than token-wise).
A hybrid backend routes small-$N$ shapes (e.g.\ GQA K/V projections) to
cuBLASLt and large-$N$ shapes (FFN, lm\_head) to Triton, recovering the best
path at every shape.

On MATH500 with DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B, the hybrid backend matches the
best Std@Acc across batch sizes in the comparison (tied with BF16 baseline
and Triton at $0.0115$, below LayerCast's $0.0141$) while running
$\mathbf{2.8\times}$ faster than LayerCast. Per-call GEMM overhead on
DeepSeek shapes sums to $-0.1\%$ versus the non-deterministic BF16 baseline,
compared with $+407\%$ for LayerCast. Legacy Llama-3.2-1B analysis corroborates
at the GEMM level: the Triton backend cuts token mismatches $\mathbf{54\times}$
and log-probability variance $\mathbf{57\times}$, and the $K_{\max}$ bound
predicts the 1B/8B/Phi-4 residual ordering. An $M$-padding fix closes the
GEMV/GEMM boundary, adding $2.1\times$ on 1B and $3.1\times$ on 8B in the
production KV-cache setting. End-to-end token-wise determinism is not yet attained: at the model level,
every GEMM-only fix---including LayerCast---produces different token
sequences at $bs\!=\!8$ vs.\ $bs\!=\!16$ ($0/50$ matching token sequences on
the MATH500 subset), because prefill-phase attention is unpatched by all
methods. Full token-wise determinism additionally requires a deterministic
attention path (e.g.\ FA3).
\end{abstract}

