\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Reproducibility is a basic expectation of numerical computation: the same input
should give the same output. BF16 LLM inference violates this. Running the same
model on the same prompt at $bs\!=\!1$ versus $bs\!=\!8$ can produce different
output tokens, and this is not sampling randomness. It is the structure of GPU
matrix multiplication.

On Llama-3.2-1B with greedy decoding, 15.5\% of (prompt, step, batch-size)
comparisons against the $bs\!=\!1$ reference flip the output token. Mean per-token
log-probabilities shift by $0.080\nats$ across batch sizes 2--64. These are real
changes in the discrete token sequence, not rounding noise in logits. We observe
the same behavior in vLLM~\citep{kwon2023vllm} under concurrent load.

\paragraph{Root cause.}
The culprit is cuBLAS's dynamic split-K heuristic. For a GEMM $C_{ij}=\sum_k
A_{ik}B_{jk}$, cuBLAS partitions the $K$ dimension across $S$ thread blocks. The
value of $S$ depends on $M$: at $M\!=\!1$, $S\!=\!0$ and there is no split; at
$M\!=\!32$, $S\!\in\!\{2,3,4\}$ to better utilize the GPU. Under BF16,
floating-point non-associativity means $S_1\ne S_2$ gives different outputs. The
same row of $A$ multiplied by the same $B$ produces a different result depending
on how many other rows share the batch.

\paragraph{Why prior approaches fall short.}
Three standard remedies exist. The \detflag\ flag%
\footnote{\texttt{torch.use\_deterministic\_algorithms}~\citep{pytorch2024det}.}
is ignored by cuBLAS without \texttt{CUBLAS\_WORKSPACE\_CONFIG} (condition~D,
Section~\ref{sec:decomp}); with the workspace config set, it disables every
non-deterministic CUDA op rather than just GEMM reduction, costing $+57$ to
$+83\%$ latency. The narrower \bfflag\ flag%
\footnote{\texttt{torch.backends.cuda.matmul.allow\_bf16\_reduced\_precision\_reduction}.}
restricts the cuBLAS algorithm set but does not force FP32 accumulation, so at
$M\!\ge\!32$ remaining candidates still reduce in BF16 and produce non-zero
output deviation (Table~\ref{tab:gemm_error}). LayerCast~\citep{yuan2025numerical}
keeps BF16 weights in memory but upcasts them to FP32 before every matmul.
This achieves FP32-level stability but incurs the cost of an FP32 weight
fetch per call; we measure $2.95\times$ end-to-end slowdown on DeepSeek-R1
MATH500 (Section~\ref{sec:math500}).

\paragraph{Our approach: precision amplification.}
Split-K is not the problem. It is a useful parallelism strategy, and disabling it
costs throughput. The real issue is that BF16 accumulation makes the split-K result
order-dependent. If every reduction is performed in FP32, the accumulation error is
bounded by $|\delta|\le 2K\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}}\sum_k|A_{ik}B_{jk}|$, which
we prove falls below BF16's quantization step for any shape with
$K<K_{\max}\approx7{,}700$. Any two split-K orderings then round to the same BF16
value, so split-K can vary freely while the output stays identical.

\dllm ships two backends that both deliver this. The cuBLASLt backend is a
two-phase heuristic that forces \texttt{CUBLAS\_COMPUTE\_32F} accumulation and
integrates with two lines of Python. The Triton backend is a fixed-plan GEMM
kernel that removes the heuristic-query cost, sidesteps the $K_{\max}$ bound
entirely, and delivers bit-exact batch-invariance by construction.

\paragraph{Contributions.}
We (i) attribute BF16 LLM inference non-determinism to cuBLAS's $M$-dependent
split-K selection, isolating it from attention and other ops
(Section~\ref{sec:background});
(ii) prove that FP32 accumulation masks BF16 non-associativity whenever
$K\!\le\!K_{\max}$, which covers the cuBLASLt backend
(Section~\ref{sec:method});
(iii) ship two backends: a cuBLASLt wrapper and a Triton kernel, both at
end-to-end overhead within 1\% of the non-deterministic baseline and
3--4$\times$ faster than torch's deterministic mode, with the Triton kernel
additionally bit-exact across batch sizes for every tested $K$
(Section~\ref{sec:overhead});
(iv) validate across architectures: Llama-3.2-1B mismatches drop
$\mathbf{54\times}$ under Triton and $37\times$ under cuBLASLt; Phi-4/14B and
Llama-3.1-8B reach $17.1\times$ and $7.4\times$; an $M$-padding fix adds
$2.1\times$ on 1B and $3.1\times$ on 8B in the production KV-cache setting
(Section~\ref{sec:kvcache});
(v) measure downstream impact: 35\% reduction in RL reward noise, 27\% in
distillation KL, and 6\% $\to$ 0\% MoE router flip rate on a synthetic
top-8 test (Section~\ref{sec:downstream}).

