\section{Background and Root Cause Analysis}
\label{sec:background}

\subsection{Floating-Point Non-Associativity in BF16 GEMM}

For BF16 GEMM $C = AB^\top$ where $A \in \mathbb{R}^{M \times K}$,
$B \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times K}$, the $(i,j)$-th output element is:
\begin{equation}
  C_{ij} = \sum_{k=1}^{K} A_{ik} \cdot B_{jk}.
  \label{eq:gemm}
\end{equation}
This summation is implemented by partitioning $K$ across $S$ thread blocks
(``split-K''). Each block computes a partial sum over its shard, and a separate
reduction kernel combines them:
\begin{equation}
  C_{ij} = \sum_{s=1}^{S} \underbrace{\sum_{k \in \text{shard}_s} A_{ik} B_{jk}}_{\hat{C}_{ij}^{(s)}}.
\end{equation}
In BF16, floating-point non-associativity gives
$\hat{C}^{(1)} \oplus \hat{C}^{(2)} \ne \hat{C}^{(2)} \oplus \hat{C}^{(1)}$, and
$\sum_{s=1}^{S_1}(\cdot) \ne \sum_{s=1}^{S_2}(\cdot)$ whenever $S_1 \ne S_2$
\citep{goldberg1991fp,ieee754}. The second identity is the one that bites at inference
time: the number of partial sums changes with the batch, so the output changes with
the batch.

\subsection{Dynamic Split-K Selection}

cuBLAS selects $S$ based on $M$. A single decode request at $M\!=\!1$ runs with no
split-K. Eight concurrent requests at $M\!=\!8$ may pick $S\!=\!2$ or $S\!=\!4$ to
better utilize the GPU. A different $S$ produces a different reduction tree, which
produces different per-element outputs.

