\section{Method: \dllm}
\label{sec:method}

\subsection{The Precision Amplification Principle}
\label{sec:theorem}

The goal is not to restrict split-K, which costs parallelism, but to amplify
precision at the reduction step so any ordering rounds to the same BF16 output.

\begin{theorem}[Precision Amplification for Batch-Invariant GEMM]
\label{thm:pa}
Let $C_{ij} = \sum_{k=1}^{K} A_{ik} B_{jk}$ be a BF16 GEMM output element.  Denote by
$\hat{C}_{ij}^{(\pi)}$ the floating-point sum computed under permutation $\pi$ of the
$K$ terms using FP32 arithmetic.  Then for any two permutations $\pi_1, \pi_2$:
\[
  |\hat{C}_{ij}^{(\pi_1)} - \hat{C}_{ij}^{(\pi_2)}|
  \;\le\; 2\,\gamma_K^{(32)} \cdot \sum_{k=1}^{K} |A_{ik} B_{jk}|
\]
where $\gamma_K^{(32)} = K\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}}/(1 - K\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}})
\approx K\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}}$ \citep{higham2002accuracy}.  If this bound is
less than $\varepsilon_{\mathrm{BF16}}/2 \cdot |C_{ij}|$, then
$\mathrm{round\_bf16}(\hat{C}_{ij}^{(\pi_1)}) = \mathrm{round\_bf16}(\hat{C}_{ij}^{(\pi_2)})$,
i.e., the BF16-rounded output is \textbf{permutation-invariant}.
\end{theorem}

\begin{corollary}[Sufficiency for LLM shapes]
\label{cor:llm}
For post-LayerNorm activations $A_{ik} \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)$ and Xavier-initialized
weights $B_{jk} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1/K)$, we have
$\mathbb{E}[\sum_k |A_{ik} B_{jk}|] \approx \sqrt{K/\pi}$, giving:
\[
  |\hat{C}^{(\pi_1)} - \hat{C}^{(\pi_2)}|
  \;\lesssim\; 2 K \varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}} \cdot \sqrt{K/\pi}
  \;\approx\; 2K^{3/2} \varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}} / \sqrt{\pi}.
\]
The batch-invariance condition $2K^{3/2}\varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}}/\sqrt{\pi} <
\varepsilon_{\mathrm{BF16}}/2$ holds for:
\[
  K \;<\; K_{\max} \;=\; \left(\frac{\sqrt{\pi}\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{BF16}}}{4\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{FP32}}}\right)^{2/3}
  \;\approx\; 7{,}700.
\]
Attention projections use $K\!=\!\text{hidden\_dim}$ (4{,}096 for Llama-8B), satisfying
$K < K_{\max}$ for all tested models.  FFN projections in large models can exceed the
bound: Llama-3.1-8B has $K_{\mathrm{FFN}}\!=\!14{,}336 > K_{\max}$, explaining the
lower 7.4$\times$ improvement on 8B vs.\ 37$\times$ on 1B.  For extreme activations
($\|a\|_\infty \gg 1$), the bound tightens and empirical verification remains necessary.
\end{corollary}

\textbf{Implication.}
FP32 accumulation guarantees batch-invariant BF16 outputs for attention projections
in every standard LLM we examined, since $K\!\le\!8{,}192<K_{\max}$, and for FFN
projections whenever the hidden dimension is at most 4{,}096. Split-K parallelism
can be kept, provided all reductions are in FP32. This differs from the
``disable split-K'' approach in a concrete way: we control the reduction precision
rather than forbidding the reduction.

\paragraph{Why FP32 accumulation rather than compensated summation.}
Compensated summation schemes~\citep{demmel2013accurate,rump2010accurate} (Kahan,
pairwise, block-compensated) give bit-exact reproducibility at a lower precision.
They are the right tool if one needs the \emph{same} result on every hardware.
Our goal is weaker: identical BF16 output regardless of split-K count. For this,
any precision level that hides the non-associativity error under BF16 quantization
works, and FP32 accumulation is the cheapest way to get there. It costs one
extra accumulator register per thread and uses the FP32 compute path that GPU
tensor cores already expose via \texttt{CUBLAS\_COMPUTE\_32F}. Kahan summation
doubles the arithmetic ops per reduction step, and pairwise summation requires
a custom kernel with a non-standard memory access pattern. Neither buys us
anything beyond what FP32 accumulation already does at our $K$ range.

\subsection{Implementation}
\label{sec:impl}

We provide two backends that both deliver batch-invariant output, trading off
between deployability and hardness of the guarantee.

\paragraph{Backend 1: Triton kernel (recommended, constructive guarantee).}
A single Triton GEMM kernel where each output tile is computed by exactly one
program, with FP32 accumulation inside a sequential reduction over $K$ at fixed
block size. Different batch sizes launch different grid dimensions but the
per-element reduction path stays byte-identical, so the output is
\textbf{bit-exact batch-invariant by construction}, independent of $K$.
This sidesteps the $K_{\max}$ bound entirely for the covered ops. Autotune runs
once per $(M_{\text{class}}, N, K)$ at first call and the plan is cached; there
is no per-call heuristic cost.

\paragraph{Backend 2: Two-phase cuBLASLt heuristic.}
The second backend is a CUDA extension that wraps cuBLASLt with
\texttt{CUBLAS\_COMPUTE\_32F}. Phase~1 requests \texttt{REDUCTION\_SCHEME\_NONE}
(no split-K); Phase~2 falls back to the \texttt{COMPUTE\_TYPE} scheme (split-K
with FP32 inter-CTA reduction) when Phase~1 returns no candidate. This is the
path our Theorem~\ref{thm:pa} argument covers: the FP32 reduction error falls
below BF16's quantization step for $K<K_{\max}$, so different split counts round
to the same BF16 value. The backend is useful when a Triton toolchain is
unavailable and works out-of-the-box against the stock cuBLAS library. It pays
$\sim 25\mu s$ per-call heuristic cost and does not cover $K>K_{\max}$.

\paragraph{Row-major layout (cuBLASLt backend only).}
cuBLASLt defaults to column-major. Without \texttt{CUBLASLT\_ORDER\_ROW} on
PyTorch's row-major tensors, element $(i,j)$ of an $[M,K]$ matrix is read at
offset $i+j\cdot K$, reaching up to $(M\!-\!1)+(K\!-\!1)K\!\approx\!K^2$
elements past the buffer end. GPU writes are asynchronous; the error surfaces
later as \texttt{CUBLAS\_STATUS\_INTERNAL\_ERROR} on the next call. The Triton
backend avoids this because it manages strides explicitly in the kernel.

\paragraph{Coverage.}
\dllm patches \texttt{F.linear} for all projection GEMMs (attention
$q/k/v/o$-proj and FFN up/gate/down). For end-to-end token-wise
determinism across batch compositions, opting into the
\texttt{attn=True} flag also patches \texttt{torch.matmul} and
\texttt{torch.bmm}: both operands are upcast BF16$\to$FP32 around the
attention score matmul (Q$\otimes$K$^\top$) and the score$\times$V
matmul. FP32 reductions sit far below BF16's quantisation step, so the
result is invariant to cuBLAS's batch-dependent split-K choice. The
cost is one extra BF16/FP32 cast per attention call; attention is
$<\!5\%$ of decode FLOPs, so end-to-end overhead is negligible.

\paragraph{GEMV/GEMM padding fix.}
Production KV-cache serving needs one extra step. When the flattened batch
dimension is $M\!=\!1$, \dllm expands the activation to $[2,K]$ by duplicating
row~0 before the cuBLASLt call and discards the duplicate from the output. cuBLAS
then always takes the GEMM code path. This eliminates the GEMV/GEMM boundary for
attention shapes up to $K\!=\!2{,}048$, which covers every attention projection in
Llama-3.2-1B.

\paragraph{Python interface.}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption={\dllm Python integration.}]
import determ_llm
determ_llm.enable()                        # Triton backend, default
determ_llm.enable(backend='cublaslt')      # cuBLASLt backend (needs no Triton)
determ_llm.enable(pad_m1=True)             # + GEMV/GEMM padding (cuBLASLt only)
determ_llm.enable(attn=True)               # + FP32-upcast attention matmul
# ... existing code unchanged ...
determ_llm.disable()
\end{lstlisting}

