\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

All experiments run on a single NVIDIA RTX A6000 (48\,GB), PyTorch 2.6.0,
CUDA 12.9. For MATH500, a second A6000 is used only to parallelize
independent eval runs, which does not affect any individual measurement.

For the MATH500 eval we use DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B~\citep{deepseekr1}
(``DeepSeek-7B'' hereafter) on the first 50 MATH500~\citep{hendrycks2021math}
problems with greedy decoding, \texttt{max\_new\_tokens}$=2048$, batch sizes
$\{8,16\}$, and seeds $\{0,1\}$, i.e.\ 4 configurations per method. Metrics
follow Yuan et al.~\citep{yuan2025numerical}: Std@Acc (standard deviation of
accuracy across configurations), Avg\_Std@Output\_Length, and Div\_Index.
The op-level bench measures per-call latency on DeepSeek-7B's 8 projection
shapes at $M\!\in\!\{1,8,16,32\}$, averaged over 100 timed iterations.
End-to-end overhead is reported on Phi-4 (14B, BF16) at batch sizes
$\{1,8,32\}$ over 10 runs of 32 output tokens. The decomposition and
production KV-cache studies use Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct (and 8B for
cross-architecture) with 10 prompts, 64 tokens, and batch sizes
$\{2,\dots,64\}$; the KV-cache protocol prefills each prompt once at
$bs\!=\!1$ and decodes at $bs\!=\!N$ with a duplicated KV state, matching
the production path in vLLM and SGLang. The vLLM integration uses vLLM
0.8.5 (V1, FA2, \texttt{enforce\_eager=True}) on Llama-3.2-1B at
$n\!\in\!\{2,4,8\}$ concurrent requests.

