\paragraph{LayerCast pays a bandwidth tax that \dllm avoids.}
LayerCast upcasts every BF16 weight to FP32 at each matmul call, which
doubles the weight-read memory bandwidth on DeepSeek's GQA workload. Our
backend keeps weights in BF16 and relies on the tensor-core BF16$\to$FP32
accumulator to avoid the bandwidth penalty; the mean per-config runtime
confirms this ($3.22\times$ vs.\ $1.11\times$). We confirm the mechanism
in the op-level bench of Section~\ref{sec:overhead}.

\paragraph{Mean accuracy spread is within sampling noise.}
At $n\!=\!50$, the $14.0\text{--}15.3\%$ spread across methods is
$\le\!0.25\sigma$ of the binomial sampling variance and does not signal
a correctness issue; the Std@Acc column isolates \emph{within-method}
consistency, which is the relevant batch-composition indicator.

\paragraph{Cross-architecture determinism is governed by attention.}
Across three models at $n\!=\!50$, \dllm cuts the median first-divergence
token lag over BF16 by 29--43\% on the GQA reasoning stacks (DeepSeek-7B:
$88\!\to\!126$; Llama-8B: $101\!\to\!142$); on the dense Phi-4 stack
($310\!\to\!382$) \dllm and LayerCast are within 1\% of each other.
End-to-end token-wise equality across bs$\in\!\{1,8,32\}$ is $0\%$ on
DeepSeek, $6$--$14\%$ on Llama, and $46$--$52\%$ on Phi-4 regardless of
method, because neither method patches attention
Q$\otimes$K$^\top$ and its non-associative softmax reductions accumulate
enough noise over $1024$ reasoning tokens to flip trajectories. The GEMM
fix remains the bottleneck for prefix stability and logprob variance,
as the Avg\_Std@top1 column and Figure~\ref{fig:sameprefix} both show.

