inside GEMM. The Triton backend removes this residual by construction.

\subsection{Serving Engine Integration (vLLM)}
\label{sec:vllm}

On vLLM 0.8.5 with Llama-3.2-1B and Flash Attention 2, BF16 produces 1--2
mismatches per batch ($n\!=\!2,4,8$ concurrent requests vs.\ $n\!=\!1$
reference). \dllm reduces $n\!=\!8$ mismatches from $2$ to $1$; the remaining
mismatch is Flash Attention 2's PagedAttention kernel, which tiles KV-cache
traversal by concurrent sequence count and is independent of \texttt{F.linear}.
Throughput drops from 940 to 553\,tok/s ($+41\%$, higher than the $+10$--$+17\%$
in Transformers) because vLLM's scheduler amplifies per-call cuBLASLt
heuristic cost; throughput also varies across runs (473--924\,tok/s) from
intermittent FP32 fallbacks in Phase~2. Full vLLM determinism additionally
needs FA3~\citep{shah2024flashattention3} or a fixed-tiling Triton attention
kernel combined with our GEMM fix.

\subsection{Downstream Impact}
\label{sec:downstream}

Three additional measurements on Llama-3.1-8B at $bs\!=\!1$ vs.\ $bs\!=\!8$
quantify what the logit drift costs common training pipelines. The RL reward
proxy (top-1 $\log P$ across batch sizes) shifts by $2.33\!\times\!10^{-2}$
nats under BF16 with paired $t$-test $p\!<\!10^{-17}$, which carries into the
importance ratios RLHF and GRPO use~\citep{ouyang2022instructgpt,schulman2017proximal,shao2024deepseekmath};
\dllm cuts the shift by $35\%$ to $1.51\!\times\!10^{-2}$. Distillation KL
between teacher softmax at the two batch sizes drops $27\%$, from
$6.36\!\times\!10^{-4}$ to $4.63\!\times\!10^{-4}$ nats, affecting $92.4\%$ of
positions above a $10^{-6}$ noise floor~\citep{hinton2015distilling,gu2024minillm}.
On a synthetic top-8 MoE router (128 experts, 1{,}000 near-tie positions),
BF16 flips $6\%$ of expert selections; \dllm flips $0$.

