\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

Yuan et al.~\citep{yuan2025numerical} (concurrent, NeurIPS 2025) quantify
BF16 inference variance across runtime configurations and propose
\textbf{LayerCast}: BF16 weights upcast to FP32 at every matmul. We use the
same FP32 compute but keep weights in BF16 and rely on the tensor-core
BF16$\to$FP32 accumulator, avoiding LayerCast's doubled weight-read
bandwidth ($3.22\times$ slower on DeepSeek MATH500; Section~\ref{sec:math500}).
We also add the $K_{\max}$ bound (Theorem~\ref{thm:pa}) characterizing when
FP32 compute guarantees batch-invariant BF16 output.
\texttt{batch\_invariant\_ops}~\citep{batchinvariantops2024} wraps reductions
at $\sim\!34\%$ overhead; we target only GEMM split-K and cut overhead
$3$--$5\times$. cuDNN/cuBLAS deterministic modes~\citep{cublas2024} restrict
algorithms; we raise reduction precision. Error-free
summation~\citep{demmel2013accurate,rump2010accurate} is bit-exact but too
expensive inner-loop. vLLM~\citep{kwon2023vllm}/SGLang~\citep{sglang2024}
deterministic modes use torch's flag plus workspace config at $+29$ to
$+83\%$ overhead. FlashAttention-3~\citep{shah2024flashattention3} gives
deterministic attention; a full stack combines it with our GEMM fix.

\textbf{Limitations and conclusion.}
\label{sec:discussion}
Prefill-phase attention and FA2's PagedAttention tile schedule remain open
(closed by FA3 in the full stack). The hybrid backend matches BF16 at
$1.11\times$ mean runtime, $2.9\times$ faster than LayerCast, and pushes
the median first-divergence token $29$--$43\%$ later than BF16 on the
reasoning models tested (Figure~\ref{fig:sameprefix}).

