\section{Proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:pa} and Corollary~\ref{cor:llm}}
\label{app:proof}

\subsection*{Notation}
Let $p_k\!=\!A_{ik}B_{jk}$ denote the $k$-th product. We treat each $p_k$ as an
FP32 value (the product $A_{ik}\cdot B_{jk}$ is computed in FP32 once the operands
are upcast from BF16; the multiplication rounds once but this error is absorbed into
the partial products we analyze below). Let $\varepsilon_{32}$ be the FP32 unit
roundoff and $\varepsilon_{16}$ the BF16 unit roundoff, with
$\varepsilon_{32}\!=\!2^{-24}$ and $\varepsilon_{16}\!=\!2^{-8}$. Write
$\gamma_n\!=\!n\varepsilon_{32}/(1-n\varepsilon_{32})$.

\subsection*{Proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:pa}}
Under any permutation $\pi$ of the indices $\{1,\dots,K\}$, the FP32 floating-point
sum $\hat C^{(\pi)}\!=\!\widehat{\sum_{k}}p_{\pi(k)}$ satisfies the standard
backward error bound~\cite[Eq.~4.4]{higham2002accuracy}:
\begin{equation}
\Bigl|\hat C^{(\pi)} - \sum_{k=1}^{K} p_k\Bigr|
\;\le\; \gamma_{K-1}\sum_{k=1}^{K}|p_k|
\;\le\; \gamma_K\sum_{k=1}^{K}|p_k|.
\label{eq:perm-bound}
\end{equation}
The bound is order-independent: it holds for every $\pi$ with the same right-hand
side. Applying the triangle inequality to two permutations $\pi_1, \pi_2$,
\begin{equation}
\bigl|\hat C^{(\pi_1)} - \hat C^{(\pi_2)}\bigr|
\;\le\; 2\,\gamma_K\sum_{k=1}^{K}|p_k|,
\label{eq:pair-bound}
\end{equation}
which is the claimed bound.

Now let $\hat y_\pi\!=\!\mathrm{round}_{\text{BF16}}(\hat C^{(\pi)})$. BF16 rounding
has the property that if two FP32 values $x_1, x_2$ lie within
$\varepsilon_{16}|C_{ij}|/2$ of each other and neither is in the rounding
tie-breaking set of $C_{ij}$, then $\mathrm{round}_{\text{BF16}}(x_1)=\mathrm{round}_{\text{BF16}}(x_2)$.
Combining this with~\eqref{eq:pair-bound}, a sufficient condition for
$\hat y_{\pi_1}=\hat y_{\pi_2}$ at every $\pi_1,\pi_2$ is
\begin{equation}
2\,\gamma_K\sum_{k=1}^{K}|p_k| \;<\; \frac{\varepsilon_{16}}{2}\,|C_{ij}|,
\label{eq:suff}
\end{equation}
which gives the invariance condition of the theorem. The ties-broken-alike
exception is a measure-zero event for continuous inputs and is negligible in
practice. $\square$

\subsection*{Proof of Corollary~\ref{cor:llm}}
Assume $A_{ik}\sim\mathcal N(0,1)$ and $B_{jk}\sim\mathcal N(0,1/K)$, which matches
post-LayerNorm activations and Xavier-initialized weights. Then
$A_{ik}B_{jk}\sim\mathcal N(0,1/K)$ pairwise independent, so
$\mathbb E|p_k|=\sqrt{2/(\pi K)}$ and
\begin{equation}
\mathbb E\!\Bigl[\sum_{k=1}^{K}|p_k|\Bigr] = K\sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi K}} = \sqrt{\frac{2K}{\pi}}.
\label{eq:expected-l1}
\end{equation}
By the central limit theorem, $C_{ij}\!\sim\!\mathcal N(0,1)$ for large $K$, so
$\mathbb E|C_{ij}|\!=\!\sqrt{2/\pi}$. Substituting $\gamma_K\!\approx\!K\varepsilon_{32}$
into~\eqref{eq:suff} and taking expectations,
\begin{equation}
2K\varepsilon_{32}\sqrt{\frac{2K}{\pi}} \;<\; \frac{\varepsilon_{16}}{2}\sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}},
\label{eq:expected-suff}
\end{equation}
which simplifies to $K^{3/2}\!<\!\varepsilon_{16}/(4\varepsilon_{32})$ and yields
$K<K_{\max}=(\varepsilon_{16}/(4\varepsilon_{32}))^{2/3}$.
Plugging in $\varepsilon_{16}/\varepsilon_{32}=2^{16}$ gives
$K_{\max}=2^{32/3}/4^{2/3}\approx7{,}700$.

\subsection*{When the bound is conservative}
The proof uses a worst-case Wilkinson bound~\eqref{eq:perm-bound}. In practice the
achieved error is smaller, for two reasons. First, the rounding errors at each
step are signed, not of fixed sign, so cancellation reduces the accumulated error
by approximately $\sqrt{K}$ under the stochastic rounding model. Second, the
condition number $\kappa(S)=\sum|p_k|/|\sum p_k|$ for post-LayerNorm activations
is typically around 30--100 for $K\!=\!4096$, rather than its worst-case
upper-bound $\mathcal O(\sqrt K)$. These two factors together make the empirical
safe $K$ larger than $K_{\max}$ in many settings (our 8B FFN result at
$K=14{,}336$ is a concrete case: $K$ exceeds the bound but the fix still helps).

