\section{Row-Major Layout Bug: Formal Analysis}
\label{app:row_major}

For a matrix $A \in \mathbb{R}^{M \times K}$ stored row-major, element $(i, j)$ resides
at byte offset $(i \cdot K + j) \cdot \text{sizeof}(\text{elem})$.  The cuBLASLt API
treats the \emph{leading dimension} as the stride between consecutive rows (row-major) or
columns (column-major).  Without setting \texttt{CUBLASLT\_ORDER\_ROW}, cuBLASLt defaults
to column-major with $\mathit{ld} = K$ (the value passed at layout creation).  Under
column-major, element $(i, j)$ is addressed at offset $i + j \cdot K$.  For
$M\!=\!2, K\!=\!4096$:
\[
  \text{max address (col-major)} = (M\!-\!1) + (K\!-\!1) \cdot K = 1 + 4095 \cdot 4096
  \approx 16.7\text{M elements},
\]
far exceeding the $M \cdot K = 8192$ element buffer.  The kernel writes out-of-bounds
silently (GPU memory access is asynchronous and does not immediately trap), corrupting
adjacent tensors.  The next cuBLAS call then fails with
\texttt{CUBLAS\_STATUS\_INTERNAL\_ERROR} because the workspace or weight tensors have
been overwritten.

